---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Integrations"
  description="CodeArmy brings the same campaign state to multiple entry points: Trae as the primary surface, CLI for automation, Feishu for collaboration, and Cluster/HPC for remote execution."
>
  <section class="container page-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Integrations</p>
    <h1>One campaign state, multiple entry points.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      CodeArmy is not locked to a single interface. The same repo-first campaign can be 
      accessed and advanced from different surfaces, each serving a distinct purpose in the 
      workflow. This page explains the hierarchy: what is your daily driver, what is for 
      automation, and what is for remote execution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="container page-body">
    <!-- Primary Entry Point -->
    <div class="split-grid" style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
      <div>
        <h2 style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem;">
          <span style="display: inline-grid; place-items: center; width: 2rem; height: 2rem; border-radius: 999px; background: var(--accent); color: #fff; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700;">1</span>
          Primary Entry Point
        </h2>
        <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          <strong>Trae Solo — Daily development surface</strong>
          <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; color: var(--muted);">
            Trae Solo is where most users spend their time. It provides the agent loop, 
            MCP tool integration, and Skills support. The campaign state lives in the repo; 
            Trae reads and writes it during your interactive sessions.
          </p>
          <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--muted);">
            <strong>When to use:</strong> Interactive planning, task execution, reviewing 
            campaign progress, and reconciling state after each work session.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2>What "shared campaign state" means</h2>
        <p class="section-copy">
          CodeArmy keeps the ground truth in the campaign repo, not in any specific tool's 
          memory. This means:
        </p>
        <ul class="page-list">
          <li>
            <strong>Trae</strong> writes task updates and progress to the repo during interactive sessions.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>CLI</strong> reads the same campaign files for scripted operations and reporting.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Remote jobs</strong> on clusters update the same artifacts that Trae will see on next sync.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Notifications</strong> to Feishu reference the same commit hashes and file paths.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="section-copy" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          The surface you use depends on context; the state you work with remains consistent.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Secondary Entry Points -->
    <div class="split-grid" style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
      <div>
        <h2 style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem;">
          <span style="display: inline-grid; place-items: center; width: 2rem; height: 2rem; border-radius: 999px; background: var(--muted); color: #fff; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700;">2</span>
          Secondary Surfaces
        </h2>
        
        <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          <strong>CLI — Automation and scripting</strong>
          <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; color: var(--muted);">
            The command-line interface is for batch operations, scheduled reconciles, 
            and CI/CD integration. It accesses the same campaign state but without 
            the interactive agent loop.
          </p>
          <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--muted);">
            <strong>When to use:</strong> Cron jobs, automated reporting, headless execution 
            on servers, and integrating with existing shell workflows.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          <strong>Feishu — Collaboration and notifications</strong>
          <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; color: var(--muted);">
            Feishu serves as a notification and lightweight review surface. It is not the 
            primary workspace but a channel for sharing summaries, requesting approvals, 
            and keeping stakeholders informed.
          </p>
          <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--muted);">
            <strong>When to use:</strong> Sending campaign summaries to team members, 
            requesting human review on completed tasks, and asynchronous status updates.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 0.75rem;">
          <span style="display: inline-grid; place-items: center; width: 2rem; height: 2rem; border-radius: 999px; background: var(--muted); color: #fff; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700;">3</span>
          Execution Environments
        </h2>
        
        <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          <strong>Cluster / HPC — Remote execution</strong>
          <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; color: var(--muted);">
            Remote clusters are where long-running experiments and compute-intensive tasks 
            actually execute. CodeArmy connects campaign state to these environments so 
            that results feed back into the repo, not just local logs.
          </p>
          <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--muted);">
            <strong>When to use:</strong> Heavy compute jobs, training runs, batch simulations, 
            and any work that needs dedicated hardware or extended runtime.
          </p>
          <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--muted); font-style: italic;">
            <strong>Note:</strong> Cluster integration requires Alice runtime configuration 
            and appropriate credentials. It is not a "zero-setup" feature.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Boundaries & Limitations -->
    <div class="callout" style="margin-bottom: 3rem; border-color: var(--warm); background: var(--warm-soft);">
      <strong>What this page does (and does not) promise</strong>
      <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; color: var(--muted);">
        CodeArmy is designed to share campaign state across surfaces, but this does not mean 
        all integrations are equally mature or require zero configuration:
      </p>
      <ul class="page-list" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
        <li>
          <strong>Trae integration</strong> is the primary focus and best-tested path.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>CLI tools</strong> are available but may require setup for your specific environment.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Feishu notifications</strong> depend on the Alice runtime having access to your 
          Feishu workspace; this is not automatic.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Cluster/HPC integration</strong> is environment-specific and requires explicit 
          configuration for job submission, data sync, and credential management.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0; color: var(--muted);">
        For a practical starting point, see <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}docs/quickstart/`}>Quickstart</a>.
        For understanding how campaigns manage state, see <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}how-it-works/`}>How It Works</a>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Navigation CTA -->
    <div class="callout" style="text-align: center;">
      <strong>Start with Trae, expand as needed</strong>
      <p style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem; color: var(--muted);">
        Most users begin with Trae Solo as their primary interface. As your workflows mature, 
        you can add CLI automation, Feishu notifications, and cluster execution without 
        changing the underlying campaign structure.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content: center;">
        <a class="button" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}docs/quickstart/`}>
          Get Started with Quickstart
        </a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}how-it-works/`}>
          Understand the Model
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
